<DocsLayout
  title="Operations"
  description="Read deployment state, follow logs and metrics, control project lifecycle, and recover previous releases."
>
  <section>
    <p class="overline">Project state</p>
    <h2>Status and deployment progress</h2>
    <p>
      Deployment work is asynchronous. The API creates a deployment record and
      the dashboard follows queued, building, running, stopped, and failed states without blocking the request.
    </p>
    <p>
      A project stream carries typed status, deployment, log, and metric events.
      The dashboard keeps the project shell stable while individual views load or reconnect.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Logs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Build output appears while the deployment is running and remains attached to deployment history.</li>
      <li>Runtime output can be loaded from recent history and followed live.</li>
      <li>Compose output includes service context and can be filtered by service or text.</li>
      <li>Secret-like values are sanitized before application logs are exposed where supported.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Metrics</h2>
    <p>
      Docker Stats provides CPU, memory, and uptime snapshots for running containers,
      streamed to the dashboard at roughly five-second intervals.
      Compose projects expose service-level selection instead of one ambiguous aggregate.
    </p>
    <p>
      Configured limits and live usage are different values. The configured number
      reserves quota; it does not mean the process continuously consumes that amount of RAM or CPU.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Lifecycle actions</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Deploy</strong></td><td>Queue a new release from the configured repository and branch.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Stop</strong></td><td>Stop the runtime and remove its active Caddy route while preserving project configuration.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Start</strong></td><td>Restart the existing runtime and restore the project route.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Restart</strong></td><td>Restart the active runtime and keep routing aligned with the resulting state.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Redeploy</strong></td><td>Build and activate a new release from source.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Deployment history and rollback</h2>
    <p>
      History records the commit, trigger source, status, timestamps, build output,
      and failure context for each deployment. A previous successful Dockerfile or
      Compose deployment can be selected for rollback without rebuilding that release.
    </p>
    <aside class="warning"><p>Static projects do not use image rollback. Redeploy the desired commit to publish its static output.</p></aside>
    <p>
      History is bounded: the 20 most recent deployments per project are kept, runtime
      log history is capped at the most recent 5,000 lines, and unused images are
      cleaned up on a weekly schedule.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Platform backups</h2>
    <p>
      The platform database is dumped to local files on a daily schedule, with optional
      weekly offsite copies to Cloudflare R2 when configured. Keep the environment
      encryption key backed up separately — without it, stored secrets cannot be recovered.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CLI access</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>mypaas</code> CLI covers routine administration without opening the
      dashboard: <code>user add</code>, <code>project list</code>, <code>project deploy</code>,
      <code>project logs</code>, and a manual <code>backup</code>. It authenticates to the
      same API with a token stored on the operator's machine.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Compose resources</h2>
    <p>
      Project settings can audit containers, networks, volumes, routes, and allocated
      ports associated with a Compose project. Reset remains explicit because deleting
      a database volume can permanently remove project data.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Database inspection</h2>
    <p>
      Owner-only DB Studio Lite can inspect PostgreSQL, MySQL, and MariaDB schemas and
      paginated rows for configured project databases. Writes require a temporary write
      session, and update or delete operations require a primary key. It is not a general raw SQL console.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
